Technical Specification – Web-Based Decision Support Tool for Apiculture
Pilot version – Departments 31 (Haute-Garonne) & 09 (Ariège)

================================================================================
SCOPE NOTE – v1 Pilot
This version covers a two-department pilot zone (Haute-Garonne – 31 and Ariège
– 09) rather than all of metropolitan France. All data processing, hosting, and
performance figures reflect this reduced scope. Extension to additional departments
or the full national coverage is planned for a later version and does not require
architecture changes beyond regenerating the .fgb file and updating the GitHub
asset path (see Section 7).
================================================================================


1. Context & Objectives

1.1 Context
Selecting an apiary location is a strategic decision that directly impacts colony
health and honey production. The primary factors are the availability of
nectar‑producing (melliferous) and pollen‑producing (polliniferous) resources
within a given radius. Currently, beekeepers lack a unified, map‑based tool that
combines these two dimensions at a fine spatial resolution.

1.2 General Objective
Develop a web‑based cartographic decision‑support application for professional and
amateur beekeepers, allowing them to evaluate the melliferous and polliniferous
potential of any location within the pilot zone (departments 31 and 09) using
public national datasets. The architecture is designed to scale to full national
coverage with minimal changes.

1.3 Specific Objectives
- Build a unified geospatial layer of melliferous and polliniferous resources from
  three open data sources (RPG, BD Forêt, Corine Land Cover), clipped to the
  bounding box of departments 31 and 09.
- Quantify the melliferous and polliniferous potential per land‑cover type and per
  time period (week/month).
- Provide an interactive map with real‑time spatial analysis (on‑the‑fly
  geospatial processing) and analytical visualisations.


2. Data Sources – Melliferous & Polliniferous Resources Only

The unified geospatial layer is constructed from three national sources applied by
order of priority, restricted to the pilot bounding box (see Section 2.2).

Priority 1: Registre Parcellaire Graphique (RPG) 2024
  WFS: https://data.geopf.fr/wfs/ows
  typename: RPG.2024:parcelles_graphiques
  Attributes: surf_parcel, code_cultu, code_group

Priority 2: BD Forêt V2 (IGN)
  WFS: https://data.geopf.fr/wfs/ows
  typename: LANDCOVER.FORESTINVENTORY.V2:formation_vegetale
  Attributes: code_tfv, tfv

Priority 3: Corine Land Cover (CLC)
  WFS: https://data.geopf.fr/wfs/ows
  typename: LANDCOVER.CLC18_FR:clc18_fr
  Attributes: code_18

Pilot bounding box (EPSG:4326, used as the BBOX filter in WFS requests):
  Departments 31 + 09 combined envelope:
    West:  0.840°E   East:  3.230°E
    South: 42.670°N  North: 43.760°N

All WFS requests are limited to this bounding box (BBOX parameter). No national
download is performed in this version.

Unified layer construction rule: see Section 2.2.

2.1 Coefficient Reference Tables (CSV)
Three independent CSV files provide coefficients, production periods, and colours.
They are fetched at application startup from their raw GitHub URLs.

RPG CSV:
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AnTp09/data_gis/main/cultures-config.csv
Foret CSV:
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AnTp09/data_gis/main/forets-config.csv
CLC CSV:
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AnTp09/data_gis/main/clc-config.csv

NOTE – Raw URLs: The URLs above use raw.githubusercontent.com to serve plain text
directly. The /blob/ GitHub viewer URLs must not be used for programmatic fetching.

Common CSV fields:
  code                  (matching code_cultu / code_tfv / code_18)
  libelle
  code_groupe           (RPG only)
  libelle_groupe        (RPG only)
  couleur               (hex color, used for polygon rendering and legend)
  coeff_mellifere       (float 0-10)
  coeff_pollinifere     (float 0-10)
  semaines_production   (integers separated by ";", e.g. 10;11;12;13;14 – ISO weeks)
  mois_production       (integers separated by ";", e.g. 3;4;5 – months 1-12)
  notes

semaines_production & mois_production format: values are integers separated by
semicolons with no spaces (e.g. "10;11;12;13;14"). In JavaScript, parse with:
  row.semaines_production.split(";").map(Number)

Join logic: For each feature in the unified layer, the code field is used to
retrieve the corresponding row from the respective CSV. The couleur field
determines polygon fill colour.

Missing code fallback: If a feature's code has no match in the CSV, the feature
is still rendered using a neutral grey colour (#AAAAAA) and is excluded from score
calculations. A console warning is emitted listing the unmatched code.

2.2 Unified Layer Construction

Reference CRS: EPSG:3857 (Web Mercator). All source layers are reprojected to
EPSG:3857 before any merge or intersection operation. This ensures direct
compatibility with OpenLayers and avoids client-side reprojection.

Pilot clip: Before any merge step, each source GeoDataFrame is clipped to the
pilot bounding box (the union geometry of departments 31 and 09, in EPSG:3857).
This keeps data volumes small and avoids processing features that are out of scope.

Priority-based spatial construction (no overlaps guaranteed):

Step 1 – Start with RPG 2024 polygons (clipped to pilot bbox) as the base.
  Their union defines the "RPG coverage mask".

Step 2 – Subtract the RPG coverage mask from BD Forêt V2 geometries using
  geopandas.overlay(how="difference"). Only BD Forêt portions outside any RPG
  parcel are retained. These fill blank spaces not covered by RPG.

Step 3 – Subtract both the RPG mask and the BD Forêt (post-difference) coverage
  from CLC geometries. Only CLC portions outside RPG and BD Forêt are retained.
  These fill remaining blank spaces.

Step 4 – Concatenate the three resulting GeoDataFrames. By construction, no two
  polygons overlap.

Topology note: Floating-point artefacts at shared boundaries are resolved by
applying buffer(0) before overlay, which is standard practice in GeoPandas to
ensure topological validity.

Output: A single FlatGeobuf file named unified_31_09.fgb, covering departments 31
and 09 only, in EPSG:3857, with a spatial index embedded (required for HTTP range
queries). This file is committed to the GitHub repository (see Section 6).

Unified layer feature properties (required for the webapp join):
  - code: string, the RPG code_cultu, BD Forêt code_tfv, or CLC code_18 (whichever
    applies), used to look up coefficients in the corresponding CSV.
  - source: string enum, one of "rpg" | "foret" | "clc" (so the client knows which
    table to join, unless a single merged lookup table is built at build time).
  Alternatively, merge-time enrichment can denormalise libelle, couleur, coefficients,
  and production weeks onto each feature to simplify the client; if so, document the
  exact property names in merge_layers.py and keep CSVs as the source of truth for
  regenerating the layer.

Expected file size: Pilot zone only (two departments, 10 m simplification) is
expected to be in the range of 30–80 MB, which fits within GitHub's per-file
limit of 100 MB. If the file exceeds 100 MB after generation, Git LFS must be
used (see Section 7.3).


3. Calculation Methods – Melliferous & Polliniferous Potential

All calculations are performed on the fly in the browser using Turf.js and a
Web Worker (see Section 4.4). No backend spatial processing.

3.1 Spatial Intersection & Area Computation
Given a circular analysis zone (radius R, centre C):
1. Load features for the analysis bounding box from the FlatGeobuf file via HTTP
   Range requests (see Section 4.3).
2. Compute intersection of each polygon with the circle using Turf.js.
3. For each intersecting polygon, calculate intersection area (m² or ha).
4. Retrieve coefficients from the reference table using the feature's code.

3.2 Global Melliferous & Polliniferous Scores
Let A_total = π × R² (total circle area)
For each intersecting type i: A_i = intersection area, m_i = coeff_mellifere,
p_i = coeff_pollinifere

Score_mellifere   = Σ(A_i × m_i) / A_total
Score_pollinifere = Σ(A_i × p_i) / A_total

Displayed as numeric values (one decimal) + optional radial gauges.

3.3 Temporal Potential (Weekly / Monthly Profile)
For each land-cover type active during week w (w ∈ semaines_production):
Nectar_week_w = Σ(A_i × m_i) for i in S_w
Pollen_week_w = Σ(A_i × p_i) for i in S_w

Normalised by the analysis circle area A_total (same weighting as global scores,
0–10 scale — not an extra “per hectare” conversion beyond dividing by circle area):
Normalised_Nectar_week_w = Nectar_week_w / A_total

Visualisation: Two overlapping line charts (nectar / pollen) with X‑axis = weeks
1–53 (or months 1–12), Y‑axis = normalised score (0–10).

3.4 Composition Breakdown
Pie or horizontal bar chart showing distribution of intersected areas by libelle.
Tooltips display area, coeff_mellifere, coeff_pollinifere.


4. Application Architecture (Frontend‑Only, On‑the‑Fly Processing)

4.1 Overall Design
Single Page Application with full‑screen map. All geospatial analysis client‑side.
Vector data is served as a single FlatGeobuf file (unified_31_09.fgb) committed
to the GitHub repository and accessed via its raw.githubusercontent.com URL.
HTTP Range requests are used so the browser fetches only the bytes needed for a
given bounding box — the full file is never downloaded.

The GitHub repository hosts both the web application code and the pilot .fgb
dataset. No external object storage is required for this version.

4.2 Technology Stack
- Cartography:         OpenLayers (v9+)
- Spatial analysis:    Turf.js (executed in a Web Worker – see Section 4.4)
- Vector data:         Single FlatGeobuf (.fgb) on GitHub, accessed via
                       raw.githubusercontent.com with HTTP Range requests;
                       flatgeobuf JS library for indexed/ranged reads
- Frontend framework:  React + Vite (or Vue.js)
- Charts:              Chart.js
- Geocoding:           API Géo Gouv (https://geo.api.gouv.fr) – client‑side

4.3 Data Flow & On‑the‑Fly Processing
1. The application holds a default URL to the raw .fgb file on GitHub (replace
   OWNER/REPO with the actual repository, e.g. apiari_gis):
     https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<OWNER>/<REPO>/main/data/unified/unified_31_09.fgb
   (configurable via environment variable VITE_UNIFIED_FGB_URL for flexibility).
   Keep CSV base URLs (Section 2.1) in the same repo or expose them via VITE_* vars
   so coefficient updates and the .fgb stay version-aligned.
2. The flatgeobuf JS library reads the file header and spatial index via an
   initial Range request. The full file is not downloaded.
3. Map rendering – For the visible viewport, features intersecting the viewport
   bbox are requested (ranged read). A zoom threshold (e.g. zoom ≥ 11) should
   gate polygon loading to avoid fetching excessive data at low zoom levels.
4. User defines zone – Circle follows mouse cursor (toggle mode). Radius set via
   slider (0.5–3 km).
5. Analysis fetch – Bounding box of the circle is computed. Features intersecting
   that bbox are fetched from the .fgb (range request). Typically a few hundred
   features for a 1–3 km radius circle.
6. On‑the‑fly intersection – Web Worker receives the fetched GeoJSON features and
   the circle geometry, computes precise intersection areas with Turf.js.
7. Aggregation – Worker joins coefficients from pre-loaded CSV JSON arrays and
   computes scores, temporal profiles, composition.
8. Rendering – Main thread receives results and updates charts and score widgets.

4.4 Performance Considerations

FlatGeobuf with HTTP Range requests on GitHub:
raw.githubusercontent.com supports HTTP Range requests, which is the mechanism
the flatgeobuf JS library uses to fetch only the relevant portion of the file
for a given bounding box. This works correctly with GitHub raw content delivery.

Expected transfer per analysis request: for a 1–3 km radius circle in the pilot
zone, the bbox query will typically retrieve a few hundred KB to a few MB of
features, depending on land-cover density. The 10 m simplification step is
essential to keep this reasonable.

Zoom threshold for map rendering: Polygon rendering from the .fgb should only be
triggered at zoom level ≥ 11 (approximately 1:70,000). At lower zoom levels,
display only the base map. This prevents large-area range requests from being
triggered by viewport panning at a national or regional scale.

Geometry simplification: Applied at 10 m tolerance (topology-preserving) before
generating the .fgb — typically Douglas–Peucker via GeoPandas/Shapely
(GeoSeries.simplify / make_valid + simplify as needed). Critical for both file
size and Turf.js intersection speed. If a different algorithm is required, document
it in methodology.md and keep tolerance comparable so file-size targets remain valid.

Web Worker for spatial analysis: All Turf.js logic runs in spatialWorker.js.
The worker receives candidate GeoJSON features from the bbox query and the circle
geometry, and posts back aggregated results to the main thread.

Reference performance target: <500 ms for ≤500 intersecting polygons on a
4-core CPU (mid-range laptop or tablet, 2023 baseline). A loading spinner is
shown during computation and during data fetch.

Caching: In-memory caching of recently fetched bbox results during the session.
IndexedDB caching of fetched ranges may be added in a later iteration.


