7. Technical Constraints & Deployment

7.1 Spatial Processing Constraints
- No server‑side spatial processing at request time. All intersections and
  aggregations run in the browser (Turf.js in a Web Worker). Heavy preprocessing
  is done offline in Python.
- Geographic coverage: Departments 31 (Haute-Garonne) and 09 (Ariège) only.
  The BBOX filter used for all WFS requests and for the clip step is:
    EPSG:4326  West: 0.840°  East: 3.230°  South: 42.670°  North: 43.760°

7.2 Performance Targets
- Initial map load:           <3 s (excluding first bbox fetch)
- Data fetch per analysis:    <3 s on typical broadband (pilot zone + simplification)
- Analysis computation:       <500 ms for ≤500 intersecting polygons after fetch
- Browser compatibility:      Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge (last 2 versions)
- Platform:                   Desktop. UI language: French.

7.3 WFS Data Fetching Strategy (download_wfs.py)
The IGN WFS endpoints enforce a maximum feature count per request (typically
1,000 features). The download_wfs.py script implements:

  a. One request set per source (RPG, BD Forêt, CLC), BBOX-filtered to the
     pilot bounding box (departments 31 + 09 combined).
  b. startIndex / count pagination: iterate until all features are retrieved
     (detect completion by: len(features) < count_requested).
  c. Retry failed requests up to 3 times with exponential backoff (1 s, 2 s, 4 s).
  d. Raw responses saved to data/raw/ per source before merging.
  e. Feature count logged per source for validation.

7.4 Deployment (GitHub-Only)

Web application:
  Deployed to GitHub Pages from the webapp/dist/ build output (gh-pages branch
  or /docs folder strategy). Free, no bandwidth limit for typical usage.
  Build command: `npm run build` in webapp/.
  The built files (HTML, JS, CSS) are small (< 5 MB total) and fully suitable
  for GitHub Pages.

Geodata (.fgb file):
  The unified_31_09.fgb is committed directly to the main branch under
  data/unified/. The browser accesses it via:
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<OWNER>/apiari_gis/main/data/unified/unified_31_09.fgb

  raw.githubusercontent.com supports HTTP Range requests, which is the exact
  mechanism the flatgeobuf JS library uses for indexed spatial queries. No CORS
  issues arise since GitHub raw content delivery includes permissive CORS headers
  (Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *).

Git LFS (if file > 100 MB):
  GitHub rejects individual files larger than 100 MB (hard limit) and warns at
  50 MB. If check_fgb_size.py reports the generated .fgb exceeds 90 MB, enable
  Git LFS before committing:

    git lfs install
    git lfs track "*.fgb"
    git add .gitattributes
    git add data/unified/unified_31_09.fgb
    git commit -m "add pilot FlatGeobuf via Git LFS"

  IMPORTANT: raw.githubusercontent.com does NOT serve Git LFS-tracked files;
  it returns an LFS pointer instead of the actual bytes. If Git LFS is needed,
  the .fgb must be attached as a GitHub Release asset and the URL updated to:
    https://github.com/<OWNER>/apiari_gis/releases/download/<tag>/unified_31_09.fgb
  GitHub Release assets are served with Range support and permissive CORS.
  Update VITE_UNIFIED_FGB_URL accordingly. For this reason, keeping the file
  under 100 MB (via geometry simplification) is strongly preferred.

Environment variable:
  VITE_UNIFIED_FGB_URL defaults to the raw GitHub URL above. Override in .env
  to point to a Release asset or any future hosting location without code changes.

7.5 Realism, Risks, and Assumptions

The pilot scope (two departments, simplified polygons, FlatGeobuf + Range reads,
and a zoom threshold) is a realistic stack for a static GitHub Pages app. Expect
iteration on:

  - WFS stability: IGN layer typenames and attribute names can change year to year
    (e.g. RPG annual update); scripts should fail loudly and docs should describe
    how to adjust typename and field mappings.
  - Turf.js cost: intersection of many complex rings can exceed the 500 ms target
    on low-end devices; 10 m simplification and optional feature caps or timeouts
    mitigate this.
  - raw.githubusercontent.com: generally supports Range and CORS for static files;
    heavy traffic can hit unauthenticated rate limits. For production scale beyond
    a small user base, mirror the .fgb on object storage or a Release asset with
    a documented URL (Section 7.4).
  - Git LFS vs raw URL: if the file exceeds 100 MB, the Release-asset URL path is
    mandatory — the spec already states this; treat staying under 100 MB as a hard
    goal for v1 simplicity.

